                type="document" xml:id="d146">
                <head>146. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a memorandum to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> dated
                    November 15, 1963, Rostow enclosed two drafts of a basic national security
                    policy. One, dated November 8, was a 14-page paper described by <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName> as “the essence.” The other was a much
                    longer paper dated November 11. Rostow stated that while the papers had
                    benefited from interagency discussion of previous drafts, they had not been seen
                    by anyone outside the Policy Planning Council. He stated that he continued to
                    believe “that promulgation of a <gloss target="#t_BNSP1">BNSP</gloss> would
                    contribute in important ways to effective, coordinated execution of U.S.
                    policy.” No record has been found of action by <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName> on this memorandum or its attachments during the remainder
                    of 1963. The memorandum is in Department of State, <gloss target="#t_S1"
                        >S</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 70 D 265, <gloss target="#t_BNSP1">BNSP</gloss>
                    1963; the two drafts are ibid., <gloss target="#t_SP1">S/P</gloss> Files: Lot 70
                    D 199, TS-<gloss target="#t_BNSP1">BNSP</gloss>.</p>
            </div>
